  "body": "Hi,\r\n\r\n#### System information\r\n\r\nGeth version: any\r\nOS & Version: Windows 10, NTFS\r\n\r\n#### Expected behaviour\r\n\r\nIt's been a known issue for a long time that the performance of some popular filesystems (particularly Microsoft brand, but I'm sure there are others) degrades significantly when there are too many files contained in a folder. To ensure good performance when using such filesystems, geth should not rely on having tens of thousands of files in the same directory. A performance increase would be noticeable if it stored the blockchain using fewer files.\r\n\r\n#### Actual behaviour\r\n\r\nI'm downloading the entire blockchain for the first time in a long time. It's near block 4,000,000, and the chaindata folder contains almost 30,000 ~2MB files. I've noticed it can take a very long time shutting down, and it spends all that time on disk I/O. With that many files in the directory, it's no surprise that I/O gets backed up.\r\n",
